Why ISIS has been able to sustain itself.
Attacks in New York, Istanbul, Dhaka, and Baghdad indicate that the grip of the Islamic State (ISIS) has reached multiple regions in Europe, North Africa, the Middle East, and Asia.
The longer the Islamic State (ISIS) maintains its strong presence in Syria and Iraq, the longer the days of its terror network concocting such mass slaughters will be.
But ISIS is not particularly difficult to eradicate.
The issue lies in that no country involved in Iraq and Syria, including the United States and its allies, has treated ISIS as the primary enemy.
This needs to change.
ISIS has a small-scale fighting force, with the United States estimating that it has between 20,000 to 25,000 members in Iraq and Syria, and around 5,000 members in Libya.
Compared to the active military personnel numbers of Syria (125,000), Iraq (271,500), Saudi Arabia (233,500), Turkey (510,600), and Iran (523,000), ISIS is utterly insignificant.
In September 2014, US President Barack Obama pledged to "strike and ultimately eliminate" ISIS, but the United States and its allies, including Saudi Arabia, Turkey, and Israel (in the background), have consistently focused on toppling Bashar al-Assad in Syria.
Recently, Brigadier-General Herzi Halevy of the Israeli army has bluntly stated (as conveyed to me by a reporter who was present at a Halevy speech): "Israel does not want to see the situation in Syria end with ISIS being defeated, a superpower withdrawing from the region, and (Israel) facing a stronger Hezbollah and Iran."
Israel opposes ISIS, but its greater concern is Iran behind Assad.
Assad has allowed Iran to support Israel's two major quasi-military adversaries — Hezbollah and Hamas.
Israel's priority is toppling Assad, rather than defeating ISIS.
Under the influence of neoconservatism, the Syrian War was for the United States a continuation of the global American hegemony plan proposed by then-Defense Secretary Richard Cheney and Deputy Secretary of State Paul Wolfowitz at the end of the Cold War.
In 1991, Wolfowitz told US General Wesley Clark:
"We did learn one thing from the Gulf War, that we can use force in the region – in the Middle East – and the Soviets won't stop us."
Before another superpower challenges us, we have about 5 to 10 years to clean up the old Soviet regime — Syria, Iran, Iraq.
The United States' multiple wars in the Middle East – Afghanistan, Iraq, Syria, Libya, and so on – were to make the Soviet Union, and subsequently Russia, exit the competition, and allow the United States to stand alone as the hegemon.
These efforts ended in disaster.
For Saudi Arabia, and for Israel, the primary target is toppling Assad to weaken Iran.
Syria is part of a massive proxy war between Shia Iran and Sunni Saudi Arabia, which has unfolded in Syria and Yemen, as well as in Bahrain and other regional countries with a propensity for sectarian divisions, including Saudi Arabia itself, where the confrontation between Shia and Sunni is more intense.
For Turkey, toppling Assad would strengthen its regional position.
But Turkey now faces three adversaries on its southern border: Assad, ISIS, and nationalist Kurds.
To date, ISIS is less of a concern for Turkey than Assad and the Kurds.
But ISIS's orchestrated terrorist attacks in Turkey may alter this situation.
Russia and Iran also pursue their own regional interests, pursuing them through proxy wars and backing quasi-military actions.
But both countries have stated their readiness to cooperate with the United States in striking ISIS, and they can also cooperate on other issues.
To date, the United States has remained unmoved because its focus is on toppling Assad.
The United States diplomatic community has condemned Russian President Putin for shielding Assad, while Russia has condemned the United States for trying to topple Assad.
These complaints appear to be mutually exclusive, but they are not.
The United States and its allies' attempts to topple Assad have violated the United Nations Charter, whereas Russia's support for Assad aligns with Syria's right to self-defense as stipulated in the charter.
Indeed, Assad is a tyrant, but the United Nations Charter does not grant any country the power to choose which tyrant to overthrow.
ISIS's persistent presence highlights three strategic flaws in US foreign policy, as well as a fatal tactical flaw.
First, the neoconservative call for toppling regimes to achieve global American hegemony is not only a bloody and ignorant mindset, but also a classic example of imperial overreach.
In every place where the United States has made such an attempt, it has ended in failure.
Syria and Libya are the latest examples.
Secondly, the CIA has long been secretly funding and training Sunni militants through Saudi Arabia.
Conversely, these militants spawned ISIS, a direct (or perhaps unintended) consequence of the policy pursued by the CIA and its Saudi partners.
Third, the United States' viewing Iran and Russia as America's unyielding enemies to a large extent is an outdated prophecy that is self-fulfilling.
Rebuilding relations with both countries is possible.
Fourth, the United States' attempt to win a two-front war against Assad and ISIS has already failed.
Whenever Assad is weakened, Sunni militants, including ISIS and the al-Nusra Front, will fill the vacuum.
If the United States, Russia, Saudi Arabia, and Iran provided air cover and logistics support, Assad and his Iraqi allies could defeat ISIS.
Indeed, Assad will continue to hold power; indeed, Russia will continue to be Syria's ally; indeed, Iran will maintain its influence there.
Terrorist attacks will undoubtedly continue to exist, perhaps for a period of time under the ISIS banner; but the organization will be driven out of its action bases in Syria and Iraq.
This outcome would not only eradicate ISIS across the Middle East; it would also lay the groundwork for a more comprehensive easing of tensions in the region.
The United States and Russia can start to turn around the recent new Cold War by jointly expelling jihadism.
(NATO's commitment to not admit Ukraine to the alliance or upgrade its East European missile defense could also be beneficial.)
There are other benefits.
Taking a cooperative approach to strike ISIS would give Saudi Arabia and Turkey reasons and opportunities to seek new temporary arrangements with Iran.
Israel's security can be strengthened by allowing Iran to build cooperative economic and geo-political relations with the West, thereby increasing the chances of a protracted Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
The rise of ISIS is a hallmark of the current strategic deficiencies of the West — particularly the United States.
The West can defeat ISIS.
The question is whether the United States will undertake the strategic reassessment needed to achieve this goal.
